<sec id="summary">
  <title>Summary</title>
  <p>Pyrgg is an easy-to-use synthetic random graph generator written in
  Python which supports various graph file formats including DIMACS .gr
  files. Pyrgg has the ability to generate graphs of different sizes and
  is designed to provide input files for broad range of graph-based
  research applications, including but not limited to testing,
  benchmarking and performance-analysis of graph processing frameworks.
  (<xref alt="Chakrabarti et al., 2004" rid="ref-Chakrabarti2004" ref-type="bibr">Chakrabarti
  et al., 2004</xref>;
  <xref alt="Zhong &amp; He, 2012" rid="ref-Zhong2012" ref-type="bibr">Zhong
  &amp; He, 2012</xref>)
  Pyrgg target audiences are computer scientists who study graph
  algorithms and graph processing frameworks.</p>
  <p>Graph Specifications :</p>
  <list list-type="bullet">
    <list-item>
      <p>Weighted</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Signed</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Self Loop</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Parallel Arc</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Sparse</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Dense</p>
    </list-item>
  </list>
  <p>Supported Formats:</p>
  <list list-type="bullet">
    <list-item>
      <p>DIMACS(.gr)</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>CSV(.csv)</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>JSON(.json)</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>YAML(.yaml)</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Weighted Edge List(.wel)</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>ASP(.lp)</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Trivial Graph Format(.tgf)</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>UCINET DL Format(.dl)</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Pickle(.p)</p>
    </list-item>
  </list>
  <p>See README.md from the Pyrgg repository for further details</p>
  <p>website : pyrgg.shaghighi.ir</p>
